@course

title: The Psychology of Design
author: Jane Mitchell
description: Explore how cognitive biases and psychological principles shape effective design decisions.
color: #6366f1
genres: design, psychology
relevant_for: UX Designers, Product Managers

@segment
Basic Design
BD

@package

@text
Design is not just about aesthetics.
It is about understanding how people think, feel, and make decisions.
In this course, we will explore the <c:r>psychological principles</c:r> behind great design.

@question
What is the primary goal of user-centered design?

answer: To solve real user problems
consequence: Exactly! UCD puts users at the center of every decision.

answer: To make things look beautiful
consequence: Aesthetics matter, but UCD focuses on solving problems first.

answer: To follow the latest trends
consequence: Trends change, but user needs remain the foundation.

correct_answers: 1
explanation: User-centered design prioritizes understanding and addressing the needs, behaviors, and pain points of real users.
hint: Think about who benefits most from the design process.

@true_false
The mere exposure effect suggests that people prefer things they are familiar with.

true: Familiarity breeds preference
consequence: Correct! Repeated exposure increases liking.

false: People always prefer novelty over familiarity
consequence: While novelty has appeal, familiarity often wins for usability.

correct_answers: 1
explanation: The mere exposure effect, discovered by Robert Zajonc, shows that repeated exposure to a stimulus increases preference for it.

@package

@text
Color is one of the most powerful tools in a designer's toolkit.
It can evoke emotions, guide attention, and communicate meaning <c:g>without a single word</c:g>.

@estimate
What percentage of first impressions are influenced by color alone?
answer: 90
explanation: Studies suggest up to 90% of snap judgments about products can be based on color alone.

@quote
Color is a power which directly influences the soul.
Wassily Kandinsky

@pause
Great progress! You are building a strong foundation in design psychology.

@package

@text
Cognitive load refers to the amount of mental effort required to process information.
Good design <c:r>reduces cognitive load</c:r> so users can focus on their goals.

@question
Which of the following reduces cognitive load?

answer: Breaking complex tasks into smaller steps
consequence: Yes! Progressive disclosure keeps things manageable.

answer: Showing all options at once
consequence: Too many options can overwhelm users.

answer: Using unfamiliar icons without labels
consequence: This increases cognitive load as users must guess meanings.

correct_answers: 1
explanation: Reducing cognitive load means simplifying the information users need to process at any given moment.
hint: The hint is...

@reflect
Think about an app you use daily.
Where does it reduce cognitive load effectively?
Where could it improve?

